  "text": "Kubernetes CNI Network Plugin Integration Architecture:\n\n## Overview\nStarting with Kubernetes 1.24, the CNI plugin invocation has been delegated entirely to the container runtime (containerd, cri-o, etc.). The kubelet no longer directly invokes CNI plugins but instead orchestrates pod creation through the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).\n\n## Key Components\n\n### 1. Pod Sandbox Creation (CNI Plugin Invocation Point)\n**File**: pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_sandbox.go\n**Function**: `createPodSandbox()` (line 39)\n\nThis function is the entry point for pod network setup. It:\n- Calls `generatePodSandboxConfig()` to create the pod sandbox configuration\n- Invokes `m.runtimeService.RunPodSandbox()` (line 68) which delegates to the container runtime\n- The container runtime is responsible for invoking the CNI plugins\n- Returns the pod sandbox ID used for subsequent operations\n\n### 2. Network Namespace and Pod Configuration\n**File**: pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_sandbox.go\n**Functions**: `generatePodSandboxConfig()` (line 79), `generatePodSandboxLinuxConfig()` (line 164)\n\nThese functions:\n- Create `PodSandboxConfig` with network settings\n- Configure network namespaces through `generatePodSandboxLinuxConfig()`\n- Pass this configuration to the runtime which sets up the network namespace before invoking CNI\n- Include hostname, DNS configuration, and port mappings\n\n### 3. Container Runtime Interface (CRI) - Network Definitions\n**File**: staging/src/k8s.io/cri-api/pkg/apis/runtime/v1/api.proto\n**Message Types**: `PodSandboxNetworkStatus` (line 567), `PodIP` (line 571)\n\nDefines the CRI protocol for network communication:\n- `PodSandboxNetworkStatus` carries the IP address(es) assigned to the pod\n- The runtime (which invokes CNI plugins) populates this with IPs obtained from IPAM\n- This is returned in the `PodSandboxStatus` after `RunPodSandbox` completes\n\n### 4. IP Address Retrieval and Pod Status Update\n**File**: pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_sandbox.go\n**Function**: `determinePodSandboxIPs()` (line 305)\n\nAfter the runtime creates the sandbox:\n- Kubelet calls `determinePodSandboxIPs()` to extract the IP(s) from the `PodSandboxStatus`\n- It parses primary IP and additional IPs returned by the runtime\n- These IPs were allocated by the CNI plugin's IPAM component during sandbox creation\n\n### 5. Pod IP Sorting and Normalization\n**File**: pkg/kubelet/kubelet_pods.go\n**Function**: `sortPodIPs()` (line 2039)\n\nNormalizes pod IPs:\n- Sorts IPs by IP family preference (IPv4 vs IPv6)\n- Returns up to 2 IPs (one per IP family)\n- Updates pod status with properly formatted IPs for cluster routing\n\n### 6. Node-Level IPAM (Pod CIDR Allocation)\n**File**: pkg/controller/nodeipam/node_ipam_controller.go\n**Type**: `Controller` (line 44)\n\nManages cluster-wide IP allocation:\n- Allocates pod CIDR ranges to nodes\n- Syncs with cloud provider (if configured)\n- Uses `legacyIPAM` or `cidrAllocator` based on configuration\n\n### 7. Pod CIDR Range Allocation\n**File**: pkg/controller/nodeipam/ipam/range_allocator.go\n**Type**: `rangeAllocator` (line 47)\n**Function**: `AllocateOrOccupyCIDR()` (line 316)\n\nAllocates CIDR ranges to nodes:\n- Assigns subnet ranges from the cluster CIDR to individual nodes\n- CNI IPAM plugins use this node CIDR to allocate individual pod IPs\n- Manages both IPv4 and IPv6 CIDR allocation\n\n## Call Chain\n\n1. **Pod Creation Request** → kubelet.syncPod()\n2. **Sandbox Creation** → kubeGenericRuntimeManager.createPodSandbox()\n   - Generates PodSandboxConfig with network settings\n   - Calls runtimeService.RunPodSandbox()\n3. **Container Runtime (containerd/crio)** executes:\n   - Creates network namespace\n   - Invokes CNI plugin executable\n   - CNI plugin calls local IPAM to allocate IP from node's pod CIDR\n   - Returns IP to runtime\n4. **Network Status Retrieval** → determinePodSandboxIPs()\n   - Extracts IP from PodSandboxNetworkStatus\n5. **Pod Status Update** → kubelet updates pod.Status.PodIPs\n   - Calls sortPodIPs() to normalize IPs\n   - Reports pod IP to API server\n\n## IPAM Flow\n\n1. **Node-Level Allocation**: \n   - NodeIPAM controller allocates /24 (or similar) CIDR to each node\n   - Kubelet passes this to container runtime via configuration\n\n2. **Pod-Level Allocation**:\n   - CNI plugins receive the node CIDR\n   - CNI IPAM (typically \"host-local\" plugin) allocates individual IPs from this range\n   - Allocations tracked locally by IPAM on the node\n\n3. **Network Plugin Coordination**:\n   - CNI plugins use the network namespace created by the runtime\n   - CNI plugins configure interfaces and routing\n   - Network status returned to kubelet for pod status reporting\n\n## Key Files Summary\n\n- **Pod creation coordination**: kuberuntime_sandbox.go, kuberuntime_manager.go\n- **IP retrieval and normalization**: kuberuntime_sandbox.go, kubelet_pods.go\n- **IPAM at node level**: pkg/controller/nodeipam/ (range_allocator.go, node_ipam_controller.go)\n- **CRI protocol definitions**: staging/src/k8s.io/cri-api/pkg/apis/runtime/v1/api.proto\n- **Runtime interface**: pkg/kubelet/container/runtime.go\n\nThe architecture cleanly separates concerns: kubelet manages pod lifecycle and IPAM at the cluster level, while container runtimes handle the actual CNI plugin invocation and pod-level IP allocation."
